<TITLE> Mumbai attack trial ends, verdict on May 3 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, Mar 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The trial of the lone surviving Pakistani gunman from the 2008 Mumbai attacks ended on Wednesday, with a verdict scheduled to be announced on May 3, Special Prosecutor Ujjwal Nikam said. Earlier, the special prosecutor and the defence attorney made their closing arguments in the special court housed in a high-security prison in central Mumbai, just over a year after the trial of Mohammad Ajmal Kasab began. "Today I am very happy that we have closed the trial and the judge has announced May 3 as the date for the verdict," Nikam told reporters. The trial, which has gripped the local media, has had several twists and turns, with the dismissal of defence attorneys, a surprise guilty plea by Kasab and the killing of an attorney for an Indian man accused of scouting Mumbai landmarks before the three-day rampage that killed at least 166 people. India had charged 38 people in connection with the case, most of them residing in Pakistan. The chargesheet ran to some 11,000 pages and the prosecution examined more than 650 witnesses. If the court finds Kasab and the two Indians charged with being members of militant group Lashkar-e-Taiba guilty, then the court may call upon the prosecutor and the defence attorney to make a submission on the sentencing, Nikam said. Kasab, who was charged on 86 counts, can be hanged if found guilty of waging war against In
